<h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>
<p>
    <code>CustomChartRenderer</code> is the single contract every chart drawing engine implements. Its one
    method, <code>render()</code>, consumes a <em>semantic</em> <code>ChartSpec</code> (the
    <a href="/projects/webcharts/">Web Charts</a> Vega-Lite L1 profile) plus the resolved
    <a href="/projects/webtheme/">webtheme</a> tokens, and returns a <code>ChartHandle</code> for updates and
    teardown. The native-first SVG default (the standard's canonical impl, shipped by Frontier UI) and every
    library adapter (<a href="https://vega.github.io/vega-lite/">Vega</a>, Plotly, ECharts) satisfy this same
    interface, which is what lets <a href="/plugs/customchartrenderregistry/">the registry</a> treat them
    interchangeably. The spec is the only lock — swapping impls leaves the <code>ChartSpec</code> untouched,
    because the renderer reads the semantic plane and resolves presentation from theme tokens, never the reverse.
</p>

<h3 id="standards">Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<we-data-table><table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://vega.github.io/vega-lite/">Vega-Lite</a></td>
        <td>De-facto grammar</td>
        <td>The L1 profile is the semantic schema the renderer consumes; renderers declare which L-tier they support.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/SVG">SVG</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>The native-first default draws with plain SVG + theme tokens, no library dependency.</td>
    </tr>
</table></we-data-table>

<h3 id="interface">Interface</h3>
{% highlight "typescript" %}
type ChartTier = 'L1' | 'L2' | 'L3';   // declared conformance tier of the Vega-Lite profile

interface ResolvedTheme {
    // webtheme tokens already resolved to concrete values for the active scheme
    [token: string]: string;
}

interface ChartHandle {
    update(spec: ChartSpec): void;     // re-render against a new semantic spec
    destroy(): void;                   // tear down DOM + listeners
}

interface CustomChartRenderer {
    readonly tier: ChartTier;          // the L-tier this engine supports
    // Draw `spec` into `target`, resolving presentation from theme tokens.
    render(target: Element, spec: ChartSpec, theme: ResolvedTheme): ChartHandle;
}
{% endhighlight %}

<h3 id="design-decisions">Design Decisions</h3>
<ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 list-disc pl-5">
    <li><strong>Semantic spec is the only lock.</strong> The renderer consumes meaning (encodings, measurement types), never presentation, so an SVG default and a Vega adapter draw the same <code>ChartSpec</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Theme application is an axis, not a fork.</strong> Presentation resolves from webtheme tokens, keeping the spec free of colours and sizes.</li>
    <li><strong>Tier declaration over a monolith.</strong> A renderer advertises its L-tier; conformance scores it on semantic fidelity, theme application, and accessibility.</li>
</ul>

<p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
